Other important features include longer maintenance periods - it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates for up to two years without returning to the home port.
Still, the permanent delays mean that the most modern warships, which were supposed to allow Germany to deploy forces outside its territory, will be outdated by the time they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The unfortunate F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media have cited a number of key software and hardware flaws that would render the ship unusable if deployed on a combat mission.
The software flaws were of particular importance because the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships would be manned by a crew of some 120 sailors - exactly half the number of people who operated the old Bremen-class frigates.
It also turned out that the ship was significantly overweight, reducing its impact and limiting the Navy's ability to add future upgrades.
It is believed that the 7,000-tonne ship Rheinland-Pfalz is twice as heavy as the similar class of ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project, including training staff, also becomes problematic.
It is said to have reached an astonishing 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion), up from the initial 2.2 billion.
The problems with the latest frigates are particularly significant in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval power is declining.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, chairman of the German Parliamentary Defence Commission, admitted that the Navy actually has deployable ships".
