A study led by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow the common bat and the species Pipistrelle, and the brown long-tailed bat and the Daubenton bat in the Inverview Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special cameras will be installed at key locations around the property to monitor bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile research using handheld detectors.
A thorough analysis of the recordings of all the records will determine the frequency of bat calls and what species they do.
Then a map of the habitat and a report will be produced to create a detailed picture of their behavior at the landscape level.
Rob Dewar, a conservation advisor at NTS, hopes the results will show which habitat areas are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help to determine the benefits of working on management of habitats, such as the creation of meadows, and which is the best way to maintain forest for bats and other related species.
The bat population in Scotland and the UK has declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work, which negatively affects the bed and the loss of housing.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose risks, including sticky paper and chemical processing of building materials, and domestic cat attacks.
Bat's not really blind.
